In C programming, we often need to go through each element of an array one by one - this is called **"iterating"** through the array. The `for` loop is perfect for this task because it lets us easily access each element using its index.
Since arrays store elements at consecutive index positions starting from `0`, the loop uses these indexes to access or modify each value.

